<br>
E and B did something alot of games don't.  They allowed the beta testers to keep their gear and levels acquired after its release.  I played for maybe a month after release.  I stopped mainly due to boring content.<br>
<br>
It’s a very pretty game, and fun to play at first, but boredom sets in fast.  There's 3 ways to get experience.  Trade, Combat and Exploring, and you need to do all 3 to keep your skills working well.  <br>
<br>
In EQ terms, trade is basically taking crates of something from Halas and running it to Grobb, then something from Grobb to Freeport and yet something else from Freeport back to Halas, rinse repeat, over and over and over.  You can do this mostly on autopilot, the only time you need to click is when you &quot;zone&quot; or take stargates in this game.  Combat is just that, combat.  You go to an area and blow junk up.  I played a Jenquai Defender.  Combat for that race and class is cloak, sneak up to a group of something, summon one out using a tractor beam of sorts and pick thorough them.  Different races do combat differently.  Progen are like Klingons, and have the ability to literally unleash hell in an all-out frontal type assault.  The terrans I played with used missiles, but their big thing is buffs and heals.  Exploring is you get experience for every new place you go and mining.  What’s kinda nifty is you can be grouped with a miner and you kill stuff and he mines.  He gets combat xp and you get exploration xp just for being grouped.<br>
<br>
There’s lots of things in between such as this new alien race poking it’s head into some of the colonized star systems and the “Red Dragons” which are like space pirates, but once you’ve seen it all you’ve literally seen it all.  Nothing new was ever added as originally promised when the game came out.  Bug reporting was always fun.  When you petition in game, you would never hear anything back, but you do get an email from someone who copy and pastes what was in your petition and that’s it.  Then you reply to that and the next day or so they email you again saying please exit the game then re-enter and if your problem still exists please petition again.<br>
<br>
Most star ports have a quest giver type computer thing.  You go over to it, click on explore, combat or trade and you have an instant quest.  Can be anything from just going outside and killing something or very long trips requiring several stops, or something simple like carrying some corporate exec to another star system.  They get really whiney when you leave them in your cargo hull and don't take them straight to where they need to go.<br>
<br>
That’s the nutshell version I guess.  It’s definitely worth checking out but for me it wasn’t something long lasting I could latch onto for any long period of time.<br>
